<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="48" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(≡ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon fremontii subsp. var. var. glabrescens" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="fremontii" subSpecies="var." variety="glabrescens">Penstemon fremontii var. glabrescens</taxonomicName>
) grows almost exclusively on steep slopes composed of Green River shale or sometimes intermixed with sandstone fragments from overlying strata. It is locally common on road cuts. It occurs primarily within the Piceance drainage with populations occurring abundantly on exposed shale along Piceance Creek and the adjacent tributaries, including the Yellow Creek drainage in Rio Blanco Co., CO. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Map showing known distribution of Penstemon luculentus in Rio Blanco and Garfield counties Colorado." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.63.7952.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/89416" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">2</figureCitation>
). It also occurs on shale slopes of the Roan Creek drainage in Garfield Co., CO. The Colorado Natural Heritage Program (CNHP) gives this taxon a global rank of G3G4T2 and a state rank of S2 due to threats from gas and oil drilling throughout its habitat in the Piceance Basin (
<bibRefCitation author="CNHP" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" publicationUrl="http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426" refId="B3" refString="CNHP, 2015. http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426 [accessed 18.12.2015]" url="http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426" year="2015">CNHP 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The ranking of G3G4 indicates a status between vulnerable and apparently secure. The rank of S2 specifies a state status of &quot;imperiled - at high risk of extinction due to very restricted range, very few populations (often 20 or fewer), recent and widespread declines, or other factors&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Rondeau, RK" journalOrPublisher="The Nature Conservancy by the Colorado Natural Heritage Program, Colorado State Univeristy, Fort Collins, Colorado" pageId="8" pageNumber="55" refId="B14" refString="Rondeau, RK, Handwerk, J, Simers, L, Granau, , Pague, C, 2011. The state of Colorado's biodiversity. The Nature Conservancy by the Colorado Natural Heritage Program, Colorado State Univeristy, Fort Collins, Colorado" title="The state of Colorado's biodiversity" year="2011">Rondeau et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Currently oil and gas drilling have not had a noticeable impact on its populations, but that could change if oil extraction begins to include the mining of oil shale.
</paragraph>
